WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:02.920
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:02.920 --> 00:00:05.080
My name is Saumitha Leelakrishnan.

00:00:05.080 --> 00:00:07.320
I'm a technical specialist,

00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:10.520
Global Emissions Center of Excellence team at Cummins.

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:15.440
I'm here to share with you a story,

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:18.820
which is a journey that is involving

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:23.160
a very interesting example of wider adoption of R

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:25.920
for business applications.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:29.160
And this story, and surprisingly,

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:32.360
starts with a deep breath.

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:35.560
If all of you could take a deep breath with me,

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:36.360
if that's OK?

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:45.680
Every day, we are breathing, and we need fresh and clean air.

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:49.119
We at Cummins recognize it.

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:53.160
Cummins leads at Inverse in innovative data-driven

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:57.119
solutions to enhance environmental stewardship

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:00.799
through emissions analysis and sustainable practices.

00:01:04.279 --> 00:01:09.919
Cummins, a Fortune 120 company, a 100-year-old history company,

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:14.639
historically a diesel engine manufacturer,

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:19.000
embraces stricter emission standards over the years

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.480
and has now broadened its portfolio

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.320
to include diverse energy sources.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:32.639
This company's investment in clean diesel and natural gas

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:35.919
and currently into electrified products and hydrogen

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:39.839
and fuel cell technology is commendable.

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:44.879
So in this talk, I'll be sharing how partnering with R

00:01:44.879 --> 00:01:49.279
has helped the global product compliance team at Cummins

00:01:49.279 --> 00:01:52.040
help deliver solutions for our customers

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:56.199
that are safe and lead to a cleaner environment.

00:01:56.199 --> 00:02:00.080
Even if you have a different data set, some of the lessons

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:02.599
that I've learned in emissions analysis

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:05.680
and environmental stewardship will definitely

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:07.519
improve your workflow.

00:02:07.519 --> 00:02:09.720
So let's dive in.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:14.360
So step one, grasp your needs.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:16.399
So for all of you in this room to understand

00:02:16.399 --> 00:02:18.559
the needs of this specific project,

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:22.279
I think I would have to give a picture of what our team does

00:02:22.279 --> 00:02:24.320
and what is the data.

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:27.199
So we are a functional excellence team

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:31.119
who are responsible for creating tools and processes

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:36.320
for onboard diagnostics and emissions compliance data.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:38.240
So what is onboard diagnostics?

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:42.119
They are systems and algorithms to detect failures

00:02:42.119 --> 00:02:46.000
that adversely affect engine emissions.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.360
Out of it, this data is very prominent,

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:51.880
the in-use monitoring performance ratio

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:55.559
that allows us to verify if the diagnostics are actively

00:02:55.559 --> 00:02:56.880
making decisions.

00:02:59.679 --> 00:03:04.039
So this onboard diagnostic data, along with a zillion

00:03:04.039 --> 00:03:08.080
of engineering data that gets collected from the engine units

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:11.600
out there in the real world, through telematics and data

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:15.240
logger devices, gets uploaded to the cloud.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:18.199
So how do I begin?

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:23.520
So I utilized extract transform load to begin with.

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:27.720
So for some of you here who are wondering about the CTL term,

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:31.919
it is the process of combining data from multiple sources

00:03:31.919 --> 00:03:34.960
and moving into a large centralized repository, often

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:36.880
called a data warehouse.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:41.440
ETL uses a set of logical rules to clean and organize

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:46.360
the data and prepare it for storage, data handling, data

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:49.199
analytics, and mission learning.

00:03:49.199 --> 00:03:52.720
So why did we use ETL?

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:55.800
High volume data sets necessitate ETL

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:57.639
for the telematics and the data logger

00:03:57.639 --> 00:04:00.919
data that gets collected from the various engine units which

00:04:00.919 --> 00:04:03.000
goes to the cloud.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.960
The onboard diagnostics data has multiple disparate sources,

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:12.720
data lake, Power BI models, relational data dictionary,

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:15.839
Excel, and many more.

00:04:15.839 --> 00:04:20.079
Data cleaning and enrichment using ETL in this example

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:25.320
is to pick the latest image data for each engine unit

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:28.399
and associate it with its equipment manufacturer's

00:04:28.399 --> 00:04:30.320
details.

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:34.679
So now that I've identified and utilized ETL,

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:37.440
the next step will be to move this data

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:40.440
to a centralized repository.

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:43.320
So to achieve this step, I worked with the analytics

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:47.880
engineering team to read the data.

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:52.880
So I worked with them to identify and set up

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:58.440
Databricks jobs to automate the execution of data processing.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.760
So the next step will be to read this data

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:03.679
from the delta lakes, which are nothing

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:05.920
but an open source storage layer.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:09.239
So for that, I utilized PySpark, which is actually

00:05:09.239 --> 00:05:12.559
nothing but an API for Apache Spark,

00:05:12.559 --> 00:05:15.239
to read the data from the delta lake

00:05:15.239 --> 00:05:19.239
and move it to a centralized repository, which in this case

00:05:19.239 --> 00:05:22.119
was a SQL database.

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:26.880
So why did we bring data to SQL?

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.559
Any guesses?

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:33.679
So because it is a relational data.

00:05:33.679 --> 00:05:36.200
So this relational data is organized

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:39.079
into three different or multiple different engine

00:05:39.079 --> 00:05:42.799
platforms, like light duty, medium duty, and heavy duty.

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:44.200
And then as you see, it's further

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:46.160
segmented into model year.

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:51.320
So different model years have its own engine families,

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:55.440
which are grouped based on fuel type, transmission, et cetera.

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.399
And each engine family can be applicable

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:02.480
to various applications, be it a truck, shuttle bus, motor coach,

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:07.920
RV, street sweeper, ambulance, like n number of applications.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:12.040
And then each application has numerous engine serial numbers.

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:14.239
For those of you who can see the last one,

00:06:14.239 --> 00:06:18.040
I think it's ESN, which stands for an engine serial number.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:20.440
So awesome.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.359
The data has arrived.

00:06:22.359 --> 00:06:26.200
So it's time to unlock its potential.

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:29.279
What kind of insights and magic do you

00:06:29.279 --> 00:06:32.320
want to extract from this data?

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:35.200
How do you envision this data transforming

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:39.040
into powerful, actionable insights?

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:42.920
So for that, you would have to move to step two.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:47.119
Use your needs as a compass.

00:06:47.119 --> 00:06:50.000
So what were the primary needs?

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.040
So we have to move from merely just describing the data

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:58.239
to making inferences and drawing conclusions.

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:04.200
Secondly, embracing machine learning algorithms

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:06.480
to extract meaningful insights.

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:09.399
So with these primary needs in mind,

00:07:09.399 --> 00:07:13.959
the idea was to build a full-blown R Shiny web

00:07:13.959 --> 00:07:18.399
application and host it in Parsit Connect app

00:07:18.399 --> 00:07:21.359
so that the 600-plus engineers who

00:07:21.359 --> 00:07:23.760
have to look into this data globally

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:26.480
will be able to utilize it.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:30.720
So the web application was built and which

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:34.040
was first able to highlight the applications that

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:37.760
required attention, then population distribution

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:40.119
of the engine serial numbers based

00:07:40.119 --> 00:07:44.480
of your application type, duty cycle, equipment

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:47.959
manufacture details, and so on and so forth,

00:07:47.959 --> 00:07:50.880
and multiple interactive visualizations,

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:55.160
and then an offline workable export as well.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:57.200
So how was this possible?

00:07:57.200 --> 00:07:58.519
So how did we boost?

00:07:58.519 --> 00:08:02.000
So I leveraged some of these packages

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:07.239
here to make the analysis truly immersive.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:13.679
So now we have a web application.

00:08:13.679 --> 00:08:15.040
Engineers can use it.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:17.799
They can derive insights from it.

00:08:17.799 --> 00:08:21.359
They have action items to work on.

00:08:21.359 --> 00:08:23.600
So what is the next step?

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:24.880
Is that all there is?

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:28.279
No, we would have to advance and adapt.

00:08:28.279 --> 00:08:30.440
So in this example, I would like to say

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:33.840
that the engine serial numbers that

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:39.359
have been identified to have presumably not accumulated

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:42.840
enough of that IOMPA ratio I mentioned earlier,

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:45.640
you need some key attributes like duty cycle

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:49.039
and application so that the engineering teams can

00:08:49.039 --> 00:08:50.799
go and analyze the data.

00:08:50.799 --> 00:08:52.880
So how do I find the duty cycle?

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:55.159
So before then, what's a duty cycle?

00:08:55.159 --> 00:09:00.280
So duty cycle is a definition of history of speed and load

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:02.119
conditions over which an engine is

00:09:02.119 --> 00:09:07.400
operating over a period of time for any selected application.

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:11.440
So I wanted to find the duty cycle with the engineering data

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:14.119
that was available in hand with me.

00:09:14.119 --> 00:09:17.400
In that case, I jumped into using

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:20.919
the simplest and the popular unsupervised machine learning

00:09:20.919 --> 00:09:23.239
model, which is k-means clustering.

00:09:23.239 --> 00:09:26.359
I utilized this Python library for it.

00:09:26.359 --> 00:09:29.799
So I worked with subject matter experts

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:35.000
to identify five engine features based on the characteristics

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.119
to determine the duty cycle.

00:09:37.119 --> 00:09:41.400
So it was idle percent, torque curve percent,

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:44.479
motoring percent, key cycles per hour,

00:09:44.479 --> 00:09:47.239
and drive cycle average percent.

00:09:47.239 --> 00:09:52.440
So once I identified these engine features,

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:56.500
how I used it in the model is that how this k-means

00:09:56.500 --> 00:10:00.119
clustering model works is that it first randomly assigns

00:10:00.119 --> 00:10:03.000
a data point to one of your clusters,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.200
and then you compute the centroid of each cluster.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:09.719
Then there is reassignment of your centroid of each data

00:10:09.719 --> 00:10:12.159
point to the nearest centroid of your cluster.

00:10:12.159 --> 00:10:14.039
And this continues going until there

00:10:14.039 --> 00:10:17.960
is no changing of your clusters happening.

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:20.919
Thus, finally, you're able to identify your duty

00:10:20.919 --> 00:10:24.919
cycle of each of the engine serial numbers out there.

00:10:24.919 --> 00:10:28.880
So that will give an insight on what conditions

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:31.200
do you think those engines were not

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:33.919
able to accumulate enough of the IOMPR ratio.

00:10:34.599 --> 00:10:37.679
So the predictive modeling is complete.

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:41.760
So they have some actionable insights.

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:46.840
So is that all there is, or is our compass taking us further?

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:48.679
Looks like it is.

00:10:48.679 --> 00:10:52.719
Because the next step is generate and analyze reports.

00:10:52.719 --> 00:10:57.799
Proactive reporting anticipates issues and opportunities

00:10:57.799 --> 00:11:02.440
in a timely manner so that you can make informed decisions.

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:07.320
So in this case, I utilized Quattro

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:10.799
to generate monthly and quarterly reports

00:11:10.799 --> 00:11:13.799
for each engine family, which will highlight

00:11:13.799 --> 00:11:18.559
the applications and the duty cycle for which the engine

00:11:18.559 --> 00:11:21.919
units were not able to accumulate enough of the IOMPR

00:11:21.919 --> 00:11:24.559
ratio that we were talking about earlier.

00:11:24.559 --> 00:11:27.799
So Quattro came in very handy.

00:11:27.799 --> 00:11:30.080
And these are some of the highlights

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.479
packages that I was able to utilize in Quattro.

00:11:33.479 --> 00:11:36.760
So NITAR, so that you can integrate your code, text,

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:37.880
and the graphs.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:41.400
Because the report had a lot of not just text.

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:46.200
It had tables, graphs, interactive visualization.

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:50.760
So CableXTRA was used to bring in pretty tables.

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:54.799
And then WebBot for interactive HTML widgets.

00:11:54.799 --> 00:11:57.520
And so that these reports were not

00:11:57.799 --> 00:12:00.880
And so that these reports were not static,

00:12:00.880 --> 00:12:06.280
you could go back to the Passit Connect app

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:08.719
that we had published earlier, which

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:11.400
is going to have many details, wherein this report is

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:13.000
something high level, right?

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.880
So the engineers and the product compliance managers

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:20.599
can have a way to interact directly with your app

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:24.479
and through your report as well.

00:12:24.479 --> 00:12:27.039
So why did we use Quattro?

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:32.159
Quattro seamlessly integrates code, text, and graphs.

00:12:32.159 --> 00:12:35.039
Quattro's batch processing automates generation

00:12:35.039 --> 00:12:37.760
of multiple reports seamlessly.

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:39.599
Because at a single point of time,

00:12:39.599 --> 00:12:43.440
you have 60, minimum 60 different engine families

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:46.640
that you would have to generate the reports for.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:51.679
And it smoothly integrates with Git for version control.

00:12:51.679 --> 00:12:54.320
And then it enables automated report generation.

00:12:57.159 --> 00:13:01.760
So now it takes us back to the last, but not the least.

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:04.239
This is the last step as we wrap up

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:07.039
this whole journey and pipeline, which

00:13:07.039 --> 00:13:09.520
is monitor and maintain.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:12.520
As long as we are able to set up this process,

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:14.880
go on seamlessly and automatically,

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:20.239
that's when we will be able to reap the best of the benefits.

00:13:20.239 --> 00:13:23.320
So a monthly and quarterly data refresh

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:26.799
was set up using ETL jobs and scripts.

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:31.400
So that the reports get generated monthly and quarterly.

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:36.479
The reports included average IUMPR computation ratios

00:13:36.479 --> 00:13:41.760
for each engine family based off your unicycle application,

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:45.200
equipment manufacture details, so on and so forth.

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:48.679
And this report included clear actions

00:13:48.679 --> 00:13:50.919
directed to the engineering teams who

00:13:50.919 --> 00:13:53.080
are working on fine tuning the system

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:55.239
performance of the engines.

00:13:55.239 --> 00:13:58.159
So that you can deduce emissions.

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:04.719
And these were generated as PDFs and available in the RConnect

00:14:04.719 --> 00:14:06.960
apps and also in a secure SharePoint location.

00:14:09.719 --> 00:14:14.640
And this is the glimpse of the whole journey.

00:14:14.640 --> 00:14:18.719
So embracing the right tools and technologies,

00:14:18.719 --> 00:14:23.840
you will be able to build sustainable solutions.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:27.960
So I also wanted to share my data reflections

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:29.640
on this journey.

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:31.799
Take the plunge.

00:14:31.799 --> 00:14:35.799
Stepping out of the ordinary and taking bold initiatives

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:39.760
drives impactful results and growth.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:42.799
Bring the productive synergy.

00:14:42.799 --> 00:14:45.840
Integrating the best of tools and methodologies,

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:52.239
be it R, Python, Databricks, SQL, Quarto, and many more,

00:14:52.239 --> 00:14:55.559
creates comprehensive solutions.

00:14:55.559 --> 00:14:58.359
Proactive automation is paramount.

00:14:58.359 --> 00:15:02.520
As demonstrated by this Quarto report example,

00:15:02.520 --> 00:15:05.960
this exemplifies and seamlessly integrates efficiency

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:09.080
into your process.

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:14.159
This talk, I hope, will benefit the data science community

00:15:14.159 --> 00:15:18.159
into understanding a real world example of how

00:15:18.159 --> 00:15:21.559
to harness the power of both R and Python

00:15:21.559 --> 00:15:24.799
when you are faced with solving a challenging problem

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:27.760
and drive innovation within your organization.

00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:30.960
Even if you are a data scientist, data engineer,

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:33.520
developer, researcher, some of the lessons

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:35.320
that I've learned and shared with you

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:38.239
will definitely help your workflow.

